Abstract
Spacetime geometry, as described by General Relativity (GR), emerges from coherence gradients in an oscillating substrate field. This paper presents Theory of Rendered Reality (TRR), which identifies the substrate mechanism underlying gravitational phenomena. A complex scalar field ψ(x,t) oscillates at carrier frequency ω_c (constrained: ω_c > 1.4 × 10¹⁵ rad/s) and couples to matter through coupling g_m [units: (m/s)²], producing the Poisson equation ∇²C = −κρ with κ = 4πG/c² [units: m³ kg⁻¹ s⁻²]. The framework reproduces GR exactly in the weak-field limit with γ_PPN = 1 by construction.
The mode-transition proximity parameter ε is defined geometrically as ε ≡ Δr/r_s, where Δr = r_c − r_s is the radial gap between the mode-sector transition radius r_c and the Schwarzschild radius r_s. Strong-field predictions: tidal Love numbers k₂ ∝ ε²; quasi-normal mode deviations δω/ω_GR ~ π/ln(1/ε); gravitational wave echo amplitude R_GW ~ exp(−2∫Im(k_ℓ)dr); and scalar breathing frequency f_s = (α/√κ_max)f₂₂ (α ≈ 3.8, numerical WKB fit). The parameter space 10⁻¹⁰ < ε < 1.49 × 10⁻⁶, κ_max > 0.95, ω_c > 1.4 × 10¹⁵ rad/s is consistent with all current observations. Four limiting cases recover GR and known physical limits. Decisive tests arrive with Einstein Telescope (2035+).



