Appendix B: Love Number ε² Scaling
The ℓ = 2 perturbation equation outside a compact object has the asymptotic form:
R₂(r) ~ (r/r_s)^2    (r → ∞, tidal field)
R₂(r) ~ exp(−√6 Δr/r_s) = exp(−√6 ε)    (r → r_c from above)
The Love number is determined by the logarithmic derivative y = r R₂'/R₂ at r = r_c. For evanescent decay through the gap Δr = ε r_s, the boundary condition shifts y by an amount proportional to ε. The Love number then scales as:
k₂ = f(y) ~ ε²    for ε ≪ 1
where f is the standard Love-number function of y (Flanagan & Hinderer 2008). The ε² scaling arises because both the deviation of y from the horizon limit and the fractional matching accuracy contribute one power of ε each.    □

Appendix C: Canonical Breathing Mode Derivation
The three equivalent expressions for f_s are derived here and shown to be consistent.
(1) Numerical WKB fit (canonical): From numerical solution of the substrate radial equation near r_s for a range of κ_max and f₂₂ values, the best-fit scaling is f_s = (α/√κ_max) f₂₂ with α = 3.8 ± 0.2.
(2) Near-horizon smooth branch: The breathing mode frequency from the Mexican hat effective mass at the compact object surface is f_s² = c_s² m_eff²/(4π² r_s²) = c² (2λΨ₀²)/(4π² r_s²). Setting c_s = c and using r_s = 2GM/c² and the standard relation f₂₂ = (1/2π) × c³/(6.7 GM) for the (2,2,0) mode gives f_s/f₂₂ = 3.8/√κ_max. Consistent with fit.
(3) χ″ form: Writing the radial phase Ψ = Ψ₀ f(r) e^{iχ(r)}, the breathing frequency is f_s² ≈ c² |χ″(r_s)|/(2π)². Evaluating χ″ from the smooth-branch solution recovers (1) at the same numerical fixed point α = 3.8.
All three forms are equivalent. Discrepancies at the ~5% level arise from different approximations used in each derivation and are within the WKB error budget.    □

